  With limited responsibilities, a diversely constituted fresh look committee could be modeled loosely after the civilian review boards that increasingly monitor police. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B200}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B200}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F200 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN200]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Most of those boards participate in the oversight of police departments in narrow ways, such as resolving complaints against individual police officers, without interfering in broader questions about the department's policing }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *1624}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  strategies. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B201}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B201}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F201 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN201]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Although police departments initially balked at even minimal civilian involvement in their affairs, at least some role for external monitoring of police is increasingly acceptable. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B202}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B202}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F202 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN202]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  If prosecutors' offices could survive a similar cultural adjustment, they could have the benefits of neutral fresh looks without sacrificing the autonomy brought by prosecutorial discretion. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B203}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B203}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F203 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN203]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
E. Prosecutorial Involvement in Innocence Projects}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Another proposal for reform is increased prosecutorial involvement in the organizations that govern and address professional ethics among lawyers generally and prosecutors specifically, such as state and local bar committees, innocence projects, and groups concerned with providing quality defense }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber38}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber38}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 representation in criminal cases. Currently, prosecutors are underrepresented in bar and pro bono oriented activities. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B204}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B204}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F204 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN204]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Apart from the benefits that might inure to these organizations from increased and diversified participation, prosecutorial involvement in such groups would provide prosecutors with a venue for behavior demonstrating their commitment to protecting innocent defendants. That objective behavioral commitment could in turn assist prosecutors in their own internal decision making by mitigating the biasing effects of cognitive dissonance.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Part II.D suggested that cognitive dissonance might prevent prosecutors from neutrally evaluating defendants' claims of innocence because ethical prosecutors may not want to believe that they have convicted, or even charged, an innocent person of a crime. Accordingly, to resist dissonance, the prosecutor might underestimate }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *1625}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  the merits of a claim to innocence. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B205}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B205}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F205 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN205]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  However, recent research on dissonance suggests that dissonance resistance can be mitigated when people are given an alternative method of affirming their own values and self-perceptions. For example, Claude Steele has theorized that cognitive dissonance results from people's desire to affirm their own sense of integrity. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B206}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B206}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F206 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN206]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  According to Steele's self-affirmation theory, a person changes her beliefs in the face of dissonant conduct because the act implies that the person is not "morally adequate" and challenges the person's self-adequacy. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B207}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B207}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F207 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN207]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  To affirm her own image, the person adjusts }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber39}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber39}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 her beliefs in response to the dissonance. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B208}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B208}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F208 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN208]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Steele's theory is consistent with this Article's suggestion that prosecutors may resist reevaluating a defendant's guilt in an attempt to preserve their own sense of professional integrity.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Steele's research provides some support not only for the theorized mechanism underlying the reaction to dissonance, but also for its corollary that belief adjustment in response to dissonance can be mitigated if people are provided an alternative mechanism for self-affirmation. For example, Steele and Liu asked subjects to write an essay supporting increases in tuition, even though the subjects opposed the hikes. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B209}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B209}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F209 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN209]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Subjects were also asked to complete a questionnaire about politics and economics. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B210}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B210}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F210 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN210]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Replicating the classic finding of cognitive dissonance, subjects generally demonstrated a change in their beliefs, reporting less opposition to tuition increases after writing essays favoring them. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B211}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B211}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F211 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN211]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  However, the researchers found that subjects who valued politics and economics, and who had affirmed their values by completing the required questionnaire, demonstrated less belief change as a result of the forced counterattitudinal essay. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B212}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B212}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F212 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN212]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  The researchers construed the }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *1626}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  data as suggesting that salient, self-affirming cognitions might help people respond objectively to information that challenges their self-image. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B213}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B213}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F213 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN213]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Similarly, in another study, researchers found that subjects who were asked }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber40}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber40}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 to write an essay opposing state funding for the construction of handicapped facilities demonstrated less change in their beliefs about the appropriateness of such facilities if they expected to have an opportunity to personally assist the handicapped after the experiment. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B214}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B214}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F214 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN214]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  These studies suggest that prosecutors could mitigate the effects of dissonance resistance on decision making by creating alternative mechanisms to support their own self images as ethical prosecutors committed to the pursuit of justice. Personal involvement in professional organizations that value legal and prosecutorial ethics might increase the prosecutor's own confidence in her commitment to protecting the innocent and may therefore decrease the likelihood of bias in evaluating claims of innocence.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
F. Repairing Brady}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  This Article's final suggestion for reform concerns a prosecutor's disclosure of evidence to the defense under Brady v. Maryland. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B215}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B215}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F215 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN215]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  The previously suggested reforms of increased prosecutorial access to information, prosecutorial training about cognitive bias, the practice of switching litigation sides, internal fresh look reviews, and prosecutorial involvement in professional organizations all carry some potential to improve a prosecutor's application of the Brady standard because they all seek to mitigate cognitive bias and will therefore increase the likelihood of an accurate assessment of }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber41}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber41}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 the exculpatory value of a piece of evidence. Additional improvement}{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *1627}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  in prosecutorial disclosure, however, requires a rethinking of Brady's materiality standard.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  As explored in Part II.C, limiting a prosecutor's constitutional disclosure obligation to evidence that poses a "reasonable probability" }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B216}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B216}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F216 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN216]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  of affecting a case's outcome invites decision making that is biased against disclosure. Because the prosecutor has already formed a theory of guilt, she will overestimate the value of inculpatory evidence, underestimate the value of the exculpatory evidence, and ultimately undercount instances of materiality. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B217}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B217}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F217 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN217]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  The problem with the Court's Brady doctrine is its use of a harmless error standard not just in determining whether the reversal of a conviction is warranted based on the nondisclosure of exculpatory evidence, but also in determining whether disclosure is required in the first place.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  This flaw results from the Court's misplaced reliance in the Brady context on the standard established in Strickland v. Washington }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B218}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B218}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F218 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN218]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  for granting a new trial based on ineffective assistance of counsel. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B219}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B219}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F219 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN219]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Importantly, unlike Brady's materiality standard, the Court's test under Strickland is a two-prong test that separates the standard for attorney performance from the question of the defendant's entitlement to a new trial should counsel fail to meet that standard. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B220}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B220}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F220 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN220]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  The first prong makes clear that the standard for attorney performance is that of "reasonably effective assistance." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber42}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber42}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B221}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B221}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F221 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN221]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  The second prong of Strickland applies as a harmless error standard, asking whether the deficiency of counsel's performance affected the trial's outcome. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B222}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B222}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F222 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN222]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  In light of the two }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *1628}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  prongs separating the standard for attorney performance from the standard for a defendant's remedy, a defense attorney who looked to Strickland for guidance about her duties of performance would be hard pressed to argue that she was professionally, ethically, and legally entitled to provide an incompetent, unreasonable defense as long as her client was a lost cause. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B223}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B223}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F223 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN223]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Unlike Strickland's two-prong test, the Court's prosecutorial disclosure jurisprudence establishes a single standard for determining both counsel's obligations and the defendant's entitlement to relief if those obligations go unmet. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B224}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B224}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F224 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN224]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  As a standard for determining the availability of postconviction relief, Brady's materiality requirement may be a sensible method of ensuring that convictions are not lightly reversed when undisclosed evidence could not have affected a case's disposition. It is not, however, a helpful pretrial standard for prosecutors trying to determine at the outset whether to disclose evidence to the defense.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The standard governing prosecutors' disclosure to the defense should be separate from the standard that determines whether a defendant's conviction should be reversed due to a failure to disclose. Importantly, to mitigate cognitive bias, the standard for disclosure should require prosecutors to }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber43}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber43}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 evaluate the potential exculpatory value of evidence from the defense's perspective, not through the lens of their preexisting theory of guilt. For example, Professor Capra suggested long ago that prosecutors should be required to disclose any evidence "favorable to the defendant's preparation or presentation of his defense." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B225}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B225}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F225 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN225]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Model Rule of Professional Conduct 3.8(d), the ethical rule governing prosecutors' disclosure of evidence, is a step in the right direction because it requires prosecutors to "make timely disclosure to the defense of all evidence or information known to the prosecutor }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *1629}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  that tends to negate the guilt of the accused or mitigates the offense." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B226}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B226}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F226 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN226]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Although the rule primarily codifies prosecutors' constitutional obligations under Brady, the provision does not contain the limitation of materiality found in the Court's due process jurisprudence. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B227}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B227}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F227 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN227]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Unfortunately, an ethical rule that governs prosecutorial disclosure is unlikely to alter the psychology of prosecutors trained to apply the well-known, constitutionally based Brady standard. As an initial matter, prosecutors receive far more training about the constitutional rules of criminal procedure than about ethical rules. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B228}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B228}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F228 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN228]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Accordingly, they may not even be aware that Model Rule 3.8(d) requires broader disclosure than Brady. Even if aware of the gap between the Model Rule and Brady's materiality standard, prosecutors may feel an obligation as an advocate to violate Model Rule 3.8(d) and to }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber44}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber44}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 pursue all constitutional means of convicting a defendant they believe is guilty. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B229}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B229}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F229 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN229]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Because prosecutors, unlike private attorneys, are members of law enforcement, empowered by the executive branch, it is not uncommon for them to think of their obligations only as law enforcement officers governed by constitutional and statutory rules, not as lawyers governed by the rules of professional conduct. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B230}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B230}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F230 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN230]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *1630}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  The failure of bar authorities to inject ethical rules into the daily practice of prosecutors does little to alter this psychology. Even prosecutors who violate their constitutional disclosure obligations are rarely disciplined. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B231}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B231}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F231 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN231]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Thus, prosecutors who fail to disclose evidence that falls under Model Rule 3.8(d), but not Brady, are unlikely to be disciplined. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B232}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B232}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F232 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN232]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  In short, the rejection of the materiality requirement by Model Rule 3.8(d), standing alone, is unlikely to alter the decision-making process of a prosecutor evaluating the exculpatory value of evidence.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Critics of Brady have suggested a variety of alternative reforms. Professor Capra has argued for a right to in camera inspection of the prosecutors' files so that a judge can fully effectuate the defendants' Brady rights. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B233}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B233}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F233 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN233]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Still others have argued for the "open file" policies already adopted by several jurisdictions in capital prosecutions. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B234}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B234}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F234 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN234]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  This Article's purpose is not to explore fully the }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *1631}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  relative strengths and weaknesses of all possible reforms. Rather, this Article's intention is to demonstrate }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber45}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber45}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 that the Brady rule should be modified to separate the standard that governs the disclosure requirement from the harmless error standard that determines the availability of a remedy if required discovery is withheld. Moreover, in light of what we know about cognitive bias, the governing standard for prosecutorial disclosure should attempt to avoid the recipe for cognitive disaster that is inherent in the current Brady standard. Broadening the Brady standard to include all favorable information, rather than just materially favorable information, would be a helpful move in the right direction. A standard turning on the favorability of the evidence instead of its materiality invites reviewing the file from the defense's perspective and therefore mitigates the influence of the prosecutor's preexisting theory of guilt on the decision-making process.}\par 
